				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Non=
-parametric method for testing whether samples originate from the same dist=
ribution</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Difference_between_ANOVA_and_KW_test.png" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Difference_between_ANOVA_and_KW_test.png/250px-Differ=
ence_between_ANOVA_and_KW_test.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"151" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"861" data-file-height=
=3D"521"></a><figcaption>Difference between ANOVA and Kruskal=E2=80=93Walli=
s test with ranks</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test</b> by ranks, <b>Kruskal=E2=80=93Wall=
is <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"=
mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math=
 xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle H}"=
>
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>H</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle H}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/75a9edddcca2f782014371f75dca39d7e13a9c1b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.064ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle H}"=
></span> test</b> (named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wil=
liam_Kruskal" title=3D"William Kruskal">William Kruskal</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Allen_Wallis" title=3D"W. Allen Wallis">W.=
 Allen Wallis</a>), or <b>one-way ANOVA on ranks</b> is a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-parametric_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Non-parametric statistics">non-parametric</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statist=
ical test">statistical test</a> for testing whether samples originate from =
the same distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-1"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is used for compar=
ing two or more independent samples of equal or different sample sizes. It =
extends the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U=
_test" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93Whitney U test">Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> =
test</a>, which is used for comparing only two groups. The parametric equiv=
alent of the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/One_way_anova" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"One way anova">=
one-way analysis of variance</a> (ANOVA).
</p><p>A significant Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test indicates that at least on=
e sample <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_dominance" tit=
le=3D"Stochastic dominance">stochastically dominates</a> one other sample. =
The test does not identify where this stochastic dominance occurs or for ho=
w many pairs of groups stochastic dominance obtains. For analyzing the spec=
ific sample pairs for stochastic dominance, Dunn's test,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Dunn_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kru=
skal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-Dunn-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> pairwise <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Mann=E2=80=93Whitney">Mann=E2=80=93Whitney</a> tests with <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonferroni_correction" title=3D"Bonferroni c=
orrection">Bonferroni correction</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conover_5-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wal=
lis_test#cite_note-Conover-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or the more powerful but less well=
 known Conover=E2=80=93Iman test<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conover_5-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_t=
est#cite_note-Conover-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> are sometimes used.
</p><p>It is supposed that the treatments significantly affect the response=
 level and then there is an order among the treatments: one tends to give t=
he lowest response, another gives the next lowest response is second, and s=
o forth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since =
it is a nonparametric method, the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test does not assu=
me a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D=
"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> of the residuals, unlike the =
analogous one-way analysis of variance. If the researcher can make the assu=
mptions of an identically shaped and scaled distribution for all groups, ex=
cept for any difference in medians, then the null hypothesis is that the me=
dians of all groups are equal, and the alternative hypothesis is that at le=
ast one population median of one group is different from the population med=
ian of at least one other group. Otherwise, it is impossible to say, whethe=
r the rejection of the null hypothesis comes from the shift in locations or=
 group dispersions. This is the same issue that happens also with the Mann-=
Whitney test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-7"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal=
%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If the data contains potential=
 outliers, if the population distributions have heavy tails, or if the popu=
lation distributions are significantly skewed, the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis t=
est is more powerful at detecting differences among treatments than <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-test" title=3D"F-test">ANOVA F-test</a>=
. On the other hand, if the population distributions are normal or are ligh=
t-tailed and symmetric, then ANOVA F-test will generally have greater power=
 which is the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it indeed s=
hould be rejected.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-10"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
