</i> tests using Dunn's test, which (1) properly employs the same rankings =
as the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test, and (2) properly employs the pooled var=
iance implied by the null hypothesis of the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test in =
order to determine which of the sample pairs are significantly different.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Dunn_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-Dunn-4"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When=
 performing multiple sample contrasts or tests, the Type I error rate tends=
 to become inflated, raising concerns about <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Multiple_comparisons_problem" title=3D"Multiple comparisons probl=
em">multiple comparisons</a>.</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Exact_probability_tables">E=
xact probability tables</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DKruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" =
title=3D"Edit section: Exact probability tables"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A large amount of computing resources is required to compute exact proba=
bilities for the Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis test. Existing software only provid=
es exact probabilities for sample sizes of less than about 30 participants.=
 These software programs rely on the asymptotic approximation for larger sa=
mple sizes. Exact probability values for larger sample sizes are available.=
 Spurrier (2003) published exact probability tables for samples as large as=
 45 participants.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#cite_note-14"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Meyer and Seaman (2006) produced exact probability distributions for =
samples as large as 105 participants.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_test#=
cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
